items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
				<jats:p>
					<jats:italic> The aim of this study was to explore cultural factors affecting burial rituals in Poland. Thirty-four university</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>students collected data from their relatives and created written narratives about deaths in their families or community.</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>Ten additional interviews were conducted with community members, a priest, and medical personnel as part of theoretical</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>sampling and verification of emerging theories. The qualitative material was administered with NVivo and analysed using</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>the Grounded Theory techniques to produce a complex description of folk beliefs, superstitions, as well as symbolic and</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>psychological meaning ascribed to traditional customs. Some of the practices were found susceptible to extinction due to</jats:italic>
					<jats:italic>industrialisation, globalisation, and cultural development</jats:italic>
				</jats:p>
title: Burial rituals and cultural changes in the polish community – a qualitative study
